1
00:00:02,393 --> 00:00:04,090
Boy, oh, boy,
am I ready for lunch.

2
00:00:04,091 --> 00:00:06,396
You're on your way, right?

3
00:00:06,397 --> 00:00:10,009
Well, I've got an appetite.

4
00:00:10,010 --> 00:00:13,577
The corner house left their
beagle out in the yard again.

5
00:00:13,578 --> 00:00:16,363
I swear, I was
running for my life.

6
00:00:18,844 --> 00:00:19,975
What in the heck?

7
00:00:19,976 --> 00:00:22,238
Hold on, Dad.

8
00:00:22,239 --> 00:00:23,761
Something's spilled in my seat.

9
00:00:23,762 --> 00:00:25,937
It's all wet.

10
00:00:25,938 --> 00:00:27,592
It smells like gasoline.

11
00:00:34,599 --> 00:00:36,035
Call 911!

12
00:00:36,036 --> 00:00:37,862
Somebody help!

13
00:00:37,863 --> 00:00:39,690
Call 911!

14
00:01:00,886 --> 00:01:02,496
Hi, sis.

15
00:01:02,497 --> 00:01:04,063
If you're calling to try
to convince me

16
00:01:04,064 --> 00:01:05,368
to talk to Dad again,

17
00:01:05,369 --> 00:01:07,196
it's a lost cause,
so let it go.

18
00:01:07,197 --> 00:01:10,025
It's not why I'm calling.

19
00:01:10,026 --> 00:01:11,679
I need some advice.

20
00:01:11,680 --> 00:01:13,463
Is everything OK?
Are the kids all right?

21
00:01:13,464 --> 00:01:15,030
No, no, no.
The kids are great.

22
00:01:15,031 --> 00:01:16,379
I just, uh--

23
00:01:16,380 --> 00:01:17,902
I just dropped
them off at school.

24
00:01:17,903 --> 00:01:22,168
Um...

25
00:01:22,169 --> 00:01:24,909
it's Brett.

26
00:01:24,910 --> 00:01:28,261
Oh, OK.

27
00:01:28,262 --> 00:01:30,393
Um, how are his
interviews going?

28
00:01:30,394 --> 00:01:31,916
There was no interview.

29
00:01:31,917 --> 00:01:33,396
I just found out
he's been lying to me

30
00:01:33,397 --> 00:01:37,096
for the last six months
about looking for a job.

31
00:01:37,097 --> 00:01:38,749
I'm sorry. What?

32
00:01:38,750 --> 00:01:40,447
All those
supposed interviews,

33
00:01:40,448 --> 00:01:43,537
and he's just been
hanging out at bars.

34
00:01:43,538 --> 00:01:45,800
OK, well, who the hell
is paying his bar tab?

35
00:01:45,801 --> 00:01:47,584
I'm keeping us afloat.

36
00:01:47,585 --> 00:01:50,413
I'm working overtime at Dad's
shop, doing the accounting.

37
00:01:50,414 --> 00:01:53,764
But between work and the kids,
I can't do this anymore.

38
00:01:53,765 --> 00:01:56,115
And to find out he's been
lying on top of all this, I--

39
00:01:56,116 --> 00:01:58,943
You're not supposed to be
doing this alone, Tink.

40
00:01:58,944 --> 00:02:02,121
You have a partner who was
supposed to be getting a job.

41
00:02:02,122 --> 00:02:04,297
I don't blame him.
I never did.

42
00:02:04,298 --> 00:02:06,168
He's had it rough.

43
00:02:06,169 --> 00:02:08,475
Tink, I'm sorry, OK?

44
00:02:08,476 --> 00:02:11,956
I'm--I'm so sorry
that this is happening.

45
00:02:11,957 --> 00:02:14,089
And I know that
he hasn't had it easy.

46
00:02:14,090 --> 00:02:18,615
But he still has to take
accountability for this, OK?

47
00:02:18,616 --> 00:02:21,444
You need to talk
to your husband, all right?

48
00:02:21,445 --> 00:02:24,186
You need to tell him
that you know and--

49
00:02:24,187 --> 00:02:25,622
I'm really sorry.

50
00:02:25,623 --> 00:02:28,190
Work is calling,
so I need to go.

51
00:02:28,191 --> 00:02:31,150
But I want you to sit down
and have a come-to-Jesus talk

52
00:02:31,151 --> 00:02:32,848
with your husband.

53
00:02:36,547 --> 00:02:37,853
Promise?

54
00:02:39,246 --> 00:02:40,768
OK.

55
00:02:40,769 --> 00:02:43,162
OK, I will.

56
00:02:43,163 --> 00:02:44,815
Thank you for listening, Nina.

57
00:02:44,816 --> 00:02:46,077
I love you.

58
00:02:46,078 --> 00:02:47,732
Mean it.

59
00:02:48,951 --> 00:02:51,518
I love you more.

60
00:02:51,519 --> 00:02:54,260
Victim's a postal worker
named Vicky Collins.

61
00:02:54,261 --> 00:02:55,565
She was halfway
through her daily route

62
00:02:55,566 --> 00:02:56,827
when her truck caught fire.

63
00:02:56,828 --> 00:02:58,307
And she suffered
third-degree burns.

64
00:02:58,308 --> 00:03:01,049
She was DOA when I got here.

65
00:03:01,050 --> 00:03:03,660
- Who's our witness?
- A guy named Conrad Wong.

66
00:03:03,661 --> 00:03:05,793
He was over there with his baby
when he saw a Black male,

67
00:03:05,794 --> 00:03:07,229
medium build,
put a package wrapped

68
00:03:07,230 --> 00:03:08,709
in duct tape in the truck.

69
00:03:08,710 --> 00:03:10,406
Figured it was just
a neighbor dropping off

70
00:03:10,407 --> 00:03:11,755
some last-minute mail till
he heard Vicky screaming

71
00:03:11,756 --> 00:03:13,148
and saw the fire.

72
00:03:13,149 --> 00:03:15,324
When he ran to help,
he saw that same Black male

73
00:03:15,325 --> 00:03:16,543
taking off headed that way.

74
00:03:16,544 --> 00:03:18,109
And what's this from?

75
00:03:18,110 --> 00:03:21,200
Part of the blanket Mr. Wong
used to try to save Vicky.

76
00:03:21,201 --> 00:03:22,505
Burned both his hands
pretty bad.

77
00:03:22,506 --> 00:03:24,203
He's at the hospital
getting treated now.

78
00:03:24,204 --> 00:03:25,726
Any other witnesses?

79
00:03:25,727 --> 00:03:27,381
Not so far.

80
00:03:30,732 --> 00:03:32,994
Going to be hard to find
any usable evidence.

81
00:03:32,995 --> 00:03:34,691
That truck had half a day's
worth of mail in it.

82
00:03:34,692 --> 00:03:36,345
Mr. Wong said it burned up
really fast.

83
00:03:36,346 --> 00:03:37,651
That's why we have the ATF

84
00:03:37,652 --> 00:03:39,435
sending out their
arson specialists.

85
00:03:39,436 --> 00:03:40,871
Can you check on his status?

86
00:03:40,872 --> 00:03:42,265
Yeah.

87
00:03:47,923 --> 00:03:51,055
Remy, this is the victim's
father, Caleb Collins.

88
00:03:51,056 --> 00:03:53,275
He's a retired firefighter
from Philadelphia.

89
00:03:53,276 --> 00:03:54,276
Special Agent Scott.

90
00:03:54,277 --> 00:03:55,321
Sorry for your loss.

91
00:03:55,322 --> 00:03:56,583
Just tell me what happened.

92
00:03:56,584 --> 00:03:58,280
We think somebody
might have planted

93
00:03:58,281 --> 00:04:00,543
an incendiary device
in the vehicle.

94
00:04:00,544 --> 00:04:03,111
Is this a case
of a crazy person

95
00:04:03,112 --> 00:04:04,721
going after postal workers

96
00:04:04,722 --> 00:04:06,288
because the letter
took too long?

97
00:04:06,289 --> 00:04:07,594
We're looking into it, OK?

98
00:04:07,595 --> 00:04:08,769
We got a full team
working on this--

99
00:04:08,770 --> 00:04:12,555
FBI, ATF,
U.S. postal inspector.

100
00:04:12,556 --> 00:04:15,079
Was Vicky working her
regular route this morning?

101
00:04:15,080 --> 00:04:17,256
Yeah, she was on her way
to pick me up for lunch

102
00:04:17,257 --> 00:04:18,735
like we do every day.

103
00:04:18,736 --> 00:04:22,086
We were on the phone,
talking about where.

104
00:04:22,087 --> 00:04:23,871
When this happened?

105
00:04:23,872 --> 00:04:25,742
Did she say she saw
anyone near her truck?

106
00:04:25,743 --> 00:04:28,136
No.

107
00:04:28,137 --> 00:04:31,139
All she said was
her seat was wet

108
00:04:31,140 --> 00:04:32,967
and it smelled like gasoline,

109
00:04:32,968 --> 00:04:38,059
and then hearing her scream

110
00:04:38,060 --> 00:04:41,281
and not being able to help
my little girl.

111
00:04:46,416 --> 00:04:47,982
I want to help.

112
00:04:47,983 --> 00:04:50,332
Well, if you want to help,
you can start by telling us,

113
00:04:50,333 --> 00:04:52,943
had she received
any threats recently?

114
00:04:52,944 --> 00:04:54,772
You think this could
have been personal?

115
00:04:56,992 --> 00:05:00,342
She was seeing
this guy, Anthony--

116
00:05:00,343 --> 00:05:02,083
real piece of work.

117
00:05:02,084 --> 00:05:04,694
Is he African American,
medium build?

118
00:05:04,695 --> 00:05:07,262
Yeah.

119
00:05:07,263 --> 00:05:10,397
Sir, if you'd come with me,
I'd like to get some more info.

120
00:05:12,964 --> 00:05:14,661
ATF is 20 minutes out.

121
00:05:14,662 --> 00:05:16,489
Ray is stuck in traffic,
but right behind them.

122
00:05:16,490 --> 00:05:17,620
Hana is looking
into an ex-boyfriend

123
00:05:17,621 --> 00:05:18,882
who might be good for this.

124
00:05:18,883 --> 00:05:20,057
Send it to Ray.

125
00:05:20,058 --> 00:05:21,798
Barnes and I will canvass
the neighborhood

126
00:05:21,799 --> 00:05:23,497
while we wait
for ATF to show up.

127
00:05:31,592 --> 00:05:33,201
Robert Jimenez?

128
00:05:33,202 --> 00:05:34,507
Yeah, that's me.

129
00:05:34,508 --> 00:05:35,812
What do we got so far?

130
00:05:35,813 --> 00:05:37,336
The char depth
and burn pattern say

131
00:05:37,337 --> 00:05:39,773
the fire originated
right behind the driver's seat.

132
00:05:39,774 --> 00:05:41,949
There's traces
of an accelerant as well.

133
00:05:41,950 --> 00:05:43,559
That's right--gasoline.

134
00:05:43,560 --> 00:05:44,995
Our victim was on the phone to
her father when it happened.

135
00:05:44,996 --> 00:05:46,301
She said she smelled it.

136
00:05:46,302 --> 00:05:47,389
A witness saw a guy
dropping off a package

137
00:05:47,390 --> 00:05:48,782
wrapped in duct tape.

138
00:05:48,783 --> 00:05:50,174
Is that what the bomb was in?

139
00:05:50,175 --> 00:05:51,393
Could be.

140
00:05:51,394 --> 00:05:52,481
I found silver fibers
under the remnants

141
00:05:52,482 --> 00:05:54,222
of a crude fire starter.

142
00:05:54,223 --> 00:05:56,485
Crude.
What do you mean, crude?

143
00:05:56,486 --> 00:05:58,269
The device is
on a time delay,

144
00:05:58,270 --> 00:05:59,836
not remotely operated.

145
00:05:59,837 --> 00:06:01,795
He probably stuffed
a shoe box with paper

146
00:06:01,796 --> 00:06:04,450
or some flammable material,
tied a lit cigarette

147
00:06:04,451 --> 00:06:06,103
to a bunch of matches,
and dropped it in.

148
00:06:06,104 --> 00:06:07,496
I found the match heads--

149
00:06:07,497 --> 00:06:08,628
simple, but lethal.

150
00:06:08,629 --> 00:06:10,064
Matches and cigarettes.

151
00:06:10,065 --> 00:06:11,849
Why does that ring a bell?

152
00:06:13,416 --> 00:06:15,330
You're thinking
of John Leonard Orr.

153
00:06:15,331 --> 00:06:16,679
Who's that?

154
00:06:16,680 --> 00:06:18,115
He was a California
fire captain

155
00:06:18,116 --> 00:06:19,769
who set about 2,000 fires.

156
00:06:19,770 --> 00:06:22,511
Same deal--he tied a lit
cigarette to a few matches.

157
00:06:22,512 --> 00:06:23,817
He left a fingerprint

158
00:06:23,818 --> 00:06:25,079
on a piece of paper
that didn't burn.

159
00:06:25,080 --> 00:06:27,734
That's how they caught
the son of a bitch.

160
00:06:27,735 --> 00:06:29,039
We're not that lucky.

161
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:30,476
No prints.

162
00:06:30,477 --> 00:06:32,173
But the match heads were
embedded in something.

163
00:06:32,174 --> 00:06:34,001
Any idea what?

164
00:06:34,002 --> 00:06:36,220
Water-gel explosive
would be my guess.

165
00:06:36,221 --> 00:06:37,657
Something like Tovarc.

166
00:06:37,658 --> 00:06:39,049
It's like dynamite,

167
00:06:39,050 --> 00:06:40,442
except a lot more stable
to transport

168
00:06:40,443 --> 00:06:41,878
and safer to handle.

169
00:06:41,879 --> 00:06:44,185
Adding Tovarc to gasoline
and a basic fire starter--

170
00:06:44,186 --> 00:06:47,536
your guy wanted to make sure
this fire burned hard and long.

171
00:06:47,537 --> 00:06:49,582
How do you get
your hands on Tovarc?

172
00:06:49,583 --> 00:06:51,714
You have to have
a license to purchase it.

173
00:06:51,715 --> 00:06:52,976
But it's not for laymen.

174
00:06:52,977 --> 00:06:54,848
And I bet your arsonist
is a layman.

175
00:06:54,849 --> 00:06:57,241
What makes you say that?

176
00:06:57,242 --> 00:06:59,679
You use an explosive
to make things explode, right?

177
00:06:59,680 --> 00:07:02,203
But Tovarc needs
a secondary charge to go off.

178
00:07:02,204 --> 00:07:05,902
Without that, it burns up
instead of exploding.

179
00:07:05,903 --> 00:07:07,861
You think our fugitive
was looking for a big bang,

180
00:07:07,862 --> 00:07:10,211
and all he got was a big fire.

181
00:07:10,212 --> 00:07:12,300
Any updates,
I want to be the first to know.

182
00:07:12,301 --> 00:07:14,433
Thank you.

183
00:07:14,434 --> 00:07:15,651
Any news on Vicky's ex?

184
00:07:15,652 --> 00:07:17,044
It wasn't him.

185
00:07:17,045 --> 00:07:18,088
He's been at the dentist

186
00:07:18,089 --> 00:07:19,176
getting his
wisdom teeth pulled.

187
00:07:19,177 --> 00:07:20,439
He's still there.

188
00:07:20,440 --> 00:07:22,615
OK. So far,
we got a Black male fugitive

189
00:07:22,616 --> 00:07:26,096
with access to a water-gel
explosive, maybe Tovarc.

190
00:07:26,097 --> 00:07:28,882
There's a million ways
to make something explode.

191
00:07:28,883 --> 00:07:30,753
This joker has a signature.

192
00:07:30,754 --> 00:07:33,626
I'll check with ViCAP
and BATS for past arsons

193
00:07:33,627 --> 00:07:36,672
involving explosives, see
if they can find me a match.

194
00:07:36,673 --> 00:07:38,761
I want to nail this piece
of garbage to the wall.

195
00:07:38,762 --> 00:07:40,763
You come after one
federal employee,

196
00:07:40,764 --> 00:07:43,113
you come after all of us.

197
00:08:03,526 --> 00:08:06,528
William, you back already?

198
00:08:06,529 --> 00:08:08,748
William?

199
00:08:08,749 --> 00:08:10,968
William, that you?

200
00:08:17,105 --> 00:08:19,628
Ugh, dang it.

201
00:08:23,154 --> 00:08:24,590
Help me.

202
00:08:24,591 --> 00:08:28,202
I need help!

203
00:08:34,557 --> 00:08:37,254
Oh, help!

204
00:08:52,357 --> 00:08:53,967
Mr. Rayson didn't make it?

205
00:08:53,968 --> 00:08:55,621
Smoke inhalation.

206
00:08:55,622 --> 00:08:57,013
Sorry to hear that.

207
00:08:57,014 --> 00:08:58,319
I tell people all the time,

208
00:08:58,320 --> 00:08:59,929
smoke can be way more
dangerous than fire.

209
00:08:59,930 --> 00:09:01,104
You find anything?

210
00:09:01,105 --> 00:09:02,628
Yeah, we got lucky.

211
00:09:02,629 --> 00:09:05,065
The arsonist left the package
at the kitchen back door.

212
00:09:05,066 --> 00:09:06,675
And this time, it didn't
completely burn up.

213
00:09:06,676 --> 00:09:09,156
Can you confirm that
this is the same arsonist

214
00:09:09,157 --> 00:09:10,853
that hit the postal truck
this morning?

215
00:09:10,854 --> 00:09:13,595
Not 100% sure, but there were
more traces of the water gel.

216
00:09:13,596 --> 00:09:15,510
I'll compare it to what
I found on the truck.

217
00:09:15,511 --> 00:09:18,252
Remy, a neighbor
walking her dog

218
00:09:18,253 --> 00:09:20,341
noticed a gray Corolla
with a Black male driver

219
00:09:20,342 --> 00:09:21,429
circling the block.

220
00:09:21,430 --> 00:09:22,952
The driver looked lost.

221
00:09:22,953 --> 00:09:26,652
NYPD is canvassing to see if
any cameras picked him up.

222
00:09:26,653 --> 00:09:28,610
Is that a witness?

223
00:09:28,611 --> 00:09:30,178
Victim's son.

224
00:09:33,224 --> 00:09:36,052
Agent Scott and Barnes, FBI.

225
00:09:36,053 --> 00:09:39,055
We're very sorry
about your father.

226
00:09:39,056 --> 00:09:40,622
I should have stayed
at home today.

227
00:09:40,623 --> 00:09:42,145
I never should have
left him alone.

228
00:09:42,146 --> 00:09:43,669
Were you his
primary caretaker?

229
00:09:43,670 --> 00:09:46,019
No, he had a nurse
who came four times a week.

230
00:09:46,020 --> 00:09:47,890
I work at a cement plant
near here.

231
00:09:47,891 --> 00:09:49,936
Is that where you were today?

232
00:09:49,937 --> 00:09:51,198
No.

233
00:09:51,199 --> 00:09:52,721
It was my day off.

234
00:09:52,722 --> 00:09:55,071
My buddy had an extra pass
to Ridgeland.

235
00:09:55,072 --> 00:09:56,638
That's a golf club
for members only.

236
00:09:56,639 --> 00:10:01,382
I jumped at the chance,
but I wish I hadn't.

237
00:10:01,383 --> 00:10:03,602
Did your father know
this woman?

238
00:10:03,603 --> 00:10:05,038
I doubt it.

239
00:10:05,039 --> 00:10:07,518
I wished he would have got
out more, made friends.

240
00:10:07,519 --> 00:10:08,650
But with his health issues,

241
00:10:08,651 --> 00:10:10,043
it just made everything
so tough on him.

242
00:10:10,044 --> 00:10:11,218
I think he missed his partner.

243
00:10:11,219 --> 00:10:12,567
He had a partner?

244
00:10:12,568 --> 00:10:14,613
No, not that kind of partner.

245
00:10:14,614 --> 00:10:17,877
He was a cop for 30 years
before turning in his badge.

246
00:10:17,878 --> 00:10:19,226
Was he a cop here?

247
00:10:19,227 --> 00:10:20,531
No, Philadelphia.

248
00:10:20,532 --> 00:10:22,533
He was head
of the aviation unit.

249
00:10:22,534 --> 00:10:24,187
OK. Thank you, Mr. Rayson.

250
00:10:24,188 --> 00:10:25,625
We appreciate
your father's service.

251
00:10:28,540 --> 00:10:30,106
Hey, Remy. What's up?

252
00:10:30,107 --> 00:10:34,154
Our latest victim is a cop
from Philly named Finn Rayson.

253
00:10:34,155 --> 00:10:36,286
And Vicky's dad,
Caleb Collins,

254
00:10:36,287 --> 00:10:39,376
was with the Philadelphia
Fire Department.

255
00:10:39,377 --> 00:10:40,987
OK, so Finn is a cop.

256
00:10:40,988 --> 00:10:42,553
And Collins is a firefighter.

257
00:10:42,554 --> 00:10:44,164
They often respond
to calls together.

258
00:10:44,165 --> 00:10:45,426
Well, depending
on the precinct

259
00:10:45,427 --> 00:10:46,906
and the fire station
they were at,

260
00:10:46,907 --> 00:10:49,038
they could have responded
to dozens of calls together.

261
